-- Molinos, Iochpe-Maxion, Petrobras, Vivo: Latin America Equity Preview
-- Nathan Gill
-- 2010-07-19T05:55:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/molinos-iochpe-maxion-petrobras-vivo-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Latin American trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous
close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  fell 2.1 percent to 3,782.33.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  
 Argentina  
 Molinos Rio de la Plata SA  (MOLI AF): Argentina’s biggest
food company may gain after the country’s national statistics
institute reported economic activity rose 12.4 percent in May
from a year earlier and 1.7 percent from the previous month. The
shares fell 1.6 percent to 15.85 pesos.  
 Brazil  
 Iochpe-Maxion SA  (MYPK3 BS): Brazil’s new vehicle sales
fell 2.2 percent to 134,909 units in the first half of July,
when compared with the same period last year, said the country’s
dealer federation, known as Fenabrave. Iochpe, a Brazilian maker
of railroad and automobile parts, rose 2.3 percent to 17.5 reais.  
 Petroleo Brasileiro SA  (PETR4 BZ): Brazil’s state-
controlled oil company received environmental licenses to begin
construction of four wind farms in Rio Grande do Norte that will
be operational by September 2011, the company said in a
regulatory filing. The shares fell 1 percent to 26.84 reais.  
 Vivo Participacoes SA  (VIVO4 BZ): Portugal Telecom SGPS
SA’s board meeting ended without an agreement on Telefonica SA’s
offer to buy the Portuguese company’s stake in the venture that
controls Vivo, Diario Economico reported on its website, without
saying where it got the information. The deadline imposed by
Telefonica is insufficient to reach a decision, the newspaper
said. Telefonica’s offer expired July 16. The shares fell 2.9
percent to 44.95 reais.  
 Mexico  
 Grupo Televisa SA  (TLEVICPO MM): The world’s largest
Spanish-language broadcaster said it sold its stake in the
controlling company of the Mexican low-cost airline Volaris for
$80.6 million. The shares fell 2 percent to 47.56 pesos.  
